<body>
<div type="description" n="monument">
<head>Description of Monument</head>
<p>A <rs type="material">white marble</rs> <rs type="objectType">altar-stele</rs> with very simple moulding above and below on three sides (<measure dim="height" type="length" unit="metre">0.83</measure> x <measure dim="width" type="length" unit="metre">0.42</measure> x <measure dim="depth" type="length" unit="metre">0.395</measure>). The upper right corner is broken, and the entire face has been pitted to take plaster. On the face the very damaged relief of a <rs type="decoration">gladiator</rs>, facing right.</p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="text">
<head>Description of Text</head>
<p><rs type="execution" key="scalpro">Inscribed</rs> on the upper moulding (ll.1-2) and on the face (l.3) above the relief</p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="letters">
<head>Letters</head>
<p>standard forms, <measure dim="height" type="length" unit="metre">0.02</measure></p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="date">
<head>Date</head>
<p>
<date notBefore="0101" notAfter="0300" exact="none">Second to third centuries A.D.</date>
 (<rs type="criteria">lettering</rs>)</p>
</div>
<div type="edition" lang="grc">
<head lang="en">Edition</head>
<ab><lb n="1"/><persName type="aphrodisian"><name reg="Νάρκισσος">Νάρκισσο<unclear reason="damage">ς</unclear></name></persName>    <w lemma="πάλος"><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">πάλου</supplied></w>    <lb n="2"/> <w lemma="ὑπό">ὑπὸ</w> <persName type="aphrodisian"><name reg="Χρυσο-">Χρυσ<unclear reason="damage">ο</unclear><gap reason="lost" extent="5" unit="character"/></name></persName>  <w lemma="πάλος"><supplied reason="lost">πά</supplied><lb n="3" type="worddiv"/> λου</w>   <g type="head"/> <num value="3">γ</num> </ab>
</div>

<div type="translation">
<head>Translation</head>
<p>Narcissus [? of brigade so-and-so] by Chryso[-] of brigade 3.</p>
</div>
<div type="commentary">
<head>Commentary</head>
<p>For the name Narcissus see Robert, Gladiateurs, 79 no. 12, and 301, Sabbatini, Roma, no.111; there are several possible resolutions of Chryso-.</p>
</div>
